recordings.loc: Tidal Channel and salt works N of El Golfo de Santa Clara, Sonora
recordings.rmk: call notes from an apparent family group of four; the species readily crosses the wide tidal channel to feed, but seems to sing only near immediate nesting territories (no foraging territories), which are all on the other side of the channel, i.e., they probably can't breed where land-based predators could easily reach them; these are call notes from this family group, but now facing into the wind at times; a little cosmetic editing of wav to remove a few very short, ugly noises; interval shortened at 1:03 to add call notes from single bird a meter up on a bush in salt grass, a harder tuck than the prior tseets;

recordings.loc: Tidal Channel and salt works N of El Golfo de Santa Clara, Sonora
recordings.rmk: singing from a half meter up in a tall patch of salt grass like Distichlis, took off in a chase, came back and resumed singing briefly, then followed another sparrow into the grass; song has been intermittent in general; it seems that a few have fledged young, and I am guessing the rest have young in the nest (and most will migrate by July?); windy; interval shortened at 2:47 by seven seconds;

recordings.loc: Tidal Channel and salt works N of El Golfo de Santa Clara, Sonora
recordings.rmk: songs, some of which I could hear faintly across the wide tidal channel in breezy conditions, but better than most of my recordings; multiple birds in view, no ability to tell how many were singing, but all of the recording involving the same few; still much problem holding the parabola steady during gusts; quality from A to E; often the only note I could hear was the terminal note, which reminded me of Horned Lark; from birds perched up on short salt grass; interval shortened at 1:30 to remove 21 seconds of partial annotation, and at 2:48 to remove 28 seconds; some of the best songs are after 3:47 and 4:53 to 7:58; interval altered at 4:14 for more from the same few birds; some 80+ birds present in the area I could scan;

This 20 second recording documents 17 Alarm Calls of an adult Savannah Sparrow (likely male). This sparrow appeared to be threatened by my presence. The Bird of North American account says "1) Alarm call:  Emphatic broadband single note. Female usually a sharp, dry chip; male either a chip or more commonly a higher pitched tsip; pitch of alarm calls of both sexes increases in frequency with perceived danger of situation." Given this statement, this was likely a male because the spectrogram shows a nearby bird that was lower pitched was 180° off axis of the microphone.
